% ====================================================================
% test_supervisor_cross_restore.trx -- VM Redux Phase 5 follow-up
% ====================================================================
% Phase 5 (commit fbf86f2) made CoroutineContext + stacks live in
% global VM, so a coroutine spawned at sl>0 survives an outer restore.
% SupervisorState was deferred from Phase 4 with rationale "natural-
% owner stays local"; once Phase 5 shipped that rationale evaporated.
%
% This test would fail pre-2026-05-08 with /invalid-restore from the
% cross-coroutine validator (the supervisor's exec stack held an above-
% barrier offset to its SupervisorState, allocated at sl>0 in local VM).
% Post-fix: SupervisorState routes through gvm_alloc<...>(...,
% ChunkKind::Supervisor); the supervisor's start-proc array also moves
% to global VM so the survival is end-to-end clean.
%
% Caller pattern: pre-intern Names at BASE (or use $/foo) and ${ } the
% start proc, mirroring every other Phase 5+ cross-restore guidance.
% ====================================================================

% rt-ok counts failures in a restore-immune slot -- string byte writes
% are unjournaled, so the count survives assertions made inside save
% scopes, and the 1-byte string lives in LOCAL VM, invisible to the
% global-heap/gc-counter probes some files assert on.  The file THROWS
% at EOF: test_all counts a file as failed only when its run throws,
% so print-only failures would slip the suite verdict.
/rt-fails 1 string def
rt-fails 0 16#0#b put
/rt-ok { exch { = } { (FAILED: ) print = rt-fails 0  rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 1 add dup 255 gt { pop 255 } if /byte-type cast  put } if-else } def

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 1: spawn supervisor at sl>0, restore back, no /invalid-restore.
% ====================================================================
% Pre-intern every Name we use as a key or value so they're below the
% sl=1 barrier and not rejected by R6 / above-barrier rules.
/sup-handle /strategy /one-for-one /intensity /period /children
/id /cross-worker /start /restart /permanent
[ ] pop pop pop pop pop pop pop pop pop pop pop

save /sv exch def

<<
  /strategy /one-for-one
  /intensity 5
  /period 30000
  /children [ << /id /cross-worker
                  /start ${ { { actor-recv pop } loop } }
                  /restart /permanent >>#$ ]#$
>>#$ supervisor /sup-handle exch def

% Supervisor spawned at sl=1; its CoroutineContext + stacks are global
% (Phase 5), its SupervisorState + start-proc array are global (this).
sv restore                                  % no /invalid-restore
true                                        (s1: restore through supervisor) rt-ok

% Yield once so the scheduler walks the live coroutine list.  If any
% offset on the surviving supervisor's stacks were dangling the walker
% would fault here.
0 100 coroutine-sleep
true                                        (s1: scheduler tick after restore) rt-ok

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 2: vm-global-info shows /supervisor in /by-kind.
% ====================================================================
vm-global-info /by-kind get /bk2 exch def
bk2 /supervisor known?
true eq                                     (s2: /supervisor in by-kind) rt-ok
bk2 /supervisor get /count get 0 gt
true eq                                     (s2: at least one supervisor block) rt-ok

rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 0 gt { /rt-assertions-failed throw } if
(test_supervisor_cross_restore: ALL TESTS PASSED) =
(__test_ok__) =
